2. Google Colab introduction¶

2.1. Overall introduction¶

Google Colab or (Colab for short) is an application developed by Google.
Colab helps us to run machine learning and especially deep learning models which required lots of computation resources.
Don't worry about your computer which has no GPU card or low RAM, Colab provide a free resources with Tesla T4 GPU and 12Gb RAM.

2.2. Colab instruction¶

Connect Colab to resources¶

And the result!

Config Colab GPU¶

Write and run code¶

Writing and running Python code in Colab is almost similar to using Jupyter notebook.

Connect to Google Drive¶

To connect to Google Drive, run the following code 

from google.colab import drive
drive.mount('/content/gdrive')

After running the code, a pop-up will appear. Click Connect to Google Drive.

A new browser tab will open. Choose the google account you want to connect.

Allow Colab to access to your google account.

If everything is ok, you will get the result.

Check folder tree in Colab¶

Show files in a folder and change folder directory¶

Run !ls to show all files and folders in a folder.
Run %cd <PATH/TO/FOLDER> to change folder directory.

Install Python library in Colab¶

Similar to Jupyter notebook !conda install -c <CHANNEL_NAME> <PACKAGE_NAME>=<VERSION> -y

3. Git and Github introduction¶

3.1. Git introduction¶

Git is a popular version control system and used for:

  • Tracking code changes
  • Tracking who made changes
  • Coding collaboration

Git helps us to:

  • Manage projects with Repositories
  • Clone a project to work on a local copy
  • Control and track changes with Staging and Committing
  • Branch and Merge to allow for work on different parts and versions of a project
  • Pull the latest version of the project to a local copy
  • Push local updates to the main project
